	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Once again this is proof of EQ&#8217;s double standards and talking with a forked tongue J <BR>
<BR>
Protecting our economy what a joke.  Let me tell you EQ&#8217;s idea of protection.  It is self not the whole.  What is good for them, not what is good for the game.  I will expand.  <BR>
<BR>
I am referring to Team (race) PvP servers.  These servers are setup for 4 teams but eventually turned into Darks (Dark Elves, Trolls, Iksars, and Ogres) vs. Lights (the rest of the races).  <BR>
<BR>
Along comes a group of thugs who&#8217;s only goal is to control the world we live (economy) in i.e. Xteamers (the X stands for the &#8220;fallen&#8221; cross since all God&#8217;s are being ignored).  <BR>
<BR>
Here is how they manage to do that:  I live on Tallon Zek so I will use Pandemonium as an example since I know little of other PvP servers except that of what I heard of at the Fan Fair.  Note: all players at the Fan Fair that played on a PvP server where against Xteaming.  <BR>
<BR>
Pandemonium is made up of lvl 55+ players of all races, few lvl 52+&#8217;s.  The only way Xteaming works is at high lvls, everyone knows that and here is why.  Low lvls don&#8217;t have enough damage ability or damage absorption to hold off higher lvl attackers and even their oor clerics cant heal them fast enough to keep them alive.  Also put a few high lvl damage dealers on the healers and the battle is over.  In PvP the strategy for wining a battle for a zone is take out the healers, casters and then melee&#8217;s.  Who ever takes out the others healers and casters first will win.  If the Dark team is fighting for possession of a zone against Pandemonium they are unable to take out the Dark healers that are protecting their light guild mates.  This gives Pandemonium the extra time needed to take out the Dark team&#8217;s healers and ultimately win the battle (this works against the Light teams that may try to fight for a zone as well so it works against both  teams).  How does this affect our economy?  That&#8217;s simple.<BR>
<BR>
Prior to Xteaming zones where fought over and this kept a balance.  Each Team formed Guilds and these Guilds formed alliances.  As Guild members need equipment or items for their epics or just to increase their performance the Guild/s would put together a raiding party and take over the zone that had those items.  They would hold that zone until the other team could muster up the forces needed to take it back.  This was the purity of the game.  <BR>
<BR>
Enter Pandemonium (funny how the name kind of implies something) and the end of this balance.  I have already explained why Xteaming is unfair since the Darks cant attack the Dark healers or the Lights cant attack the light healers.  Because of this Pandemonium can control or monopolize a zone/s with little to no effort.  By controlling a zone you control the economy (this should be apparent if not feel free to e-mail me back).  Here is how destructive this is.  Money and items are essential for the growth of a character.  Players join guilds for a variety of reasons.  One is social friends and fun, but the main reason is necessity.  We must work together to obtain certain items and to defend ourselves against our enemies and they can be either NPC or other players.  Pandemonium has not only ruined our economy by monopolization but they have manage to destroy our Guilds because we are no longer able to preserve the quality of our guilds.  This is a bonus to certain Guilds and I can explain that.  EQ is more like real life then we may think since we add the factor of human nature.  Let me enlighten a thought here.  In real life large companies can force their competition out or simply take them over by various means.  One way is a pure competitive price war, advertising or quality (your product is better then others),  But these are long battles and not too profitable.  The best way to establish high profit is to take over or bye out the competition.  In the old days you could simply blow them up or shoot them and whala you are the only bull in town and you can price gouge the heck out of population.  Praise Al Capone&#8230;long live Al Capone!  Well we kind of changed that and now we have laws that protect the people and the economy.  It still happens companies by out stocks of faltering companies and either take over management or close them down, either way the ending results are the same, they can control the prices since they are one in the same.  <BR>
<BR>
EQ character accounts can be bought in the &#8220;real life&#8221; market&#8230;eBay is an example.  So this adds a whole new perspective that I&#8217;m not going to go into but it is important we realize that accounts can be manipulated either by sale or simply friends turning over account information to friends and some real complications arise.  I am not saying we should stop friends from allowing each other to play friends accounts (because it is fun to play other characters just to learn their abilities).  I needed to add this to help understand what I am about to explain.<BR>
<BR>
On Tallon Zek both sides have a number of large Guilds.  Examples: WoZ/MoZ for the Dark team and SotG&#8217;s on the Light team.  There are others but these are directly relative to my explanation as to what I see is happening.<BR>
<BR>
WoZ is a high lvl Guild made up of lvl 50+ Dark characters.  MoZ is their low level Guild that they use to generate new characters and once they get to lvl 50 they then move to WoZ.  MOST players wishing to join WoZ MUST join MoZ.  SotG&#8217;s and WoZ are made up of long time players or players that have bought/taken over accounts with multiple high lvl characters on it.  They are also very large in size so it is not important for them to playing one of their characters at all times.  In other words they can play a different character and the Guild can function smoothly.  <BR>
<BR>
Now lets just say I am in one of these guilds and I have multiple high lvl characters.  I could very easily pull one of my characters out and join&#8230;umm Pandemonium.  I will still have a character in my Dark or Light Guild and this can be useful in a number of ways.  By monopolizing zones and items you can control the economy by price setting and item distribution.  By doing this you send players and Guilds into pandemonium lol wow where have I heard that word before.  I have experienced this first hand many of my members have gone on a Guild hoping style of life.  They think it is the inability of the Guild to provide for their needs but actually they are being led around like a mule with a jar of water dangling in front of their heads.  <BR>
<BR>
How is this an advantage to these guilds?  Let me explain another problem Guilds face.  Its called burnout.  Not game burnout but Guild burnout here is the difference.  Game burnout is where the game hold no more challenges or charm to a person.  EQ is HUGE and has years worth of challenges and aspects if you get tired make yourself new challenges and that is what Pandemonium has done.  Guild burnout is where you can no longer get members or others to believe your bullpoopy.  Guilds work best when you can rely on each other and help each other.  If you are the type that once you get what you want and are not willing to help the others get theirs then you become less able to talk them into helping you get your next item.  This ends up splitting a guild because you have a certain number that have their items and want to move on while the remainder have not gotten theirs.  This will only last so long before a player will leave your guild.  Eventually you look around and your guild is cut in half because you have had your head in the grass feeding storing up fat cells to help you get through the long winter.  While you where feeding you didn&#8217;t see your young wondering off or the wolves killing them off one by one.  Now you have to rebuild so you can get a new group of suckers to help you get your new toys.  But people aren&#8217;t falling for it anymore because you lost there trust.  That is basically Guild burnout.<BR>
<BR>
There are two ways of fighting Xteaming.  One is to create a Xteam guild of your own but this means you have to give up your pride, friends (that don&#8217;t xteam), and your God&#8217;s (role play).  My game character is a reflection of the real me.  By joining a xteam I betray my in game friends that many are my real life friends to.  In doing so I betray myself so I can not do this (join a xteam guild).  The other is to join together and hit them with pure numbers all the epics in the world couldn&#8217;t heal enough.  Okay so we disband our guilds and join WoZ (example) and create a Guild large enough to over power Pandemonium.  <BR>
<BR>
What has just happened here?  High lvls have got together to create a Xteaming Guild that will server them in two very attractive ways.  One is to get all the uber weapons they want for their characters that will be used to make God like low lvl twinks with epics (this is done a few different ways) as well as for their high level characters in either their light/dark guild or their Xteaming guild.  The other thing this achieves is to force new members into their guild so they have a new batch of hookers to pimp daddy out.  You are playing along side the very same people that have forced you into doing something you would rather not done.  <BR>
<BR>
In a manner of speaking Xteaming on a PvP server is a cheat like &#8220;God Mode&#8221; in other games.  EQ says its not a cheat but a game flaw.  Hmm game flaw isn&#8217;t that like a bug?  Doesn&#8217;t EQ fix bugs?  Its not a flaw the server rules were made &#8211; it&#8217;s a Team PvP server, by making it so that other teams can not buff or heal those of the other team, you are fixing a bug not changing the rules.  <BR>
<BR>
I bought EQ and invested time an money into it.  I play on TZ because it was designed for Team PvP and the social rule was no xteaming.  Just like loot and scoot is a social policy.  Anything can be mistreated or misinterpreted to fit any ones point of reasoning.  EQ holds Best of the Best competitions in the arena and no one is allowed to interfere.  But it&#8217;s a PvP server so if I jumped in would I be interfering or just PvPing on a PvP server?  I would be interfering and we all know it and you would stop me maybe even band me for taking advantage of a game flaw.  People will always try to take advantage of others as long as no one will stand up and knock their teeth out.  Make it not so pleasant and they will stop.  How much does EQ expect their good honest and loyal members to take before they will stand up for them?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
This can be stopped by EQ, make it so we can not Xteam on PvP servers.  Make them move not us.  Make a patch and fix the &#8220;bug&#8221;.  EQ is not changing anything but fixing it.  EQ needs to show players that they are protected or they will move to another game.  Those that change the rules and are taking advantage of the rules will NOT stay with EQ for long, only as long as it suits them.  If DaoC starts becoming a commodity on the real life market they will change in a heart beat and where is EQ then?  Shadowbane and a few other games are coming out too so if  EQ doesn&#8217;t  step carefully they will fall into a trap.<BR>
<BR>
EQ had better study their economic principles a little better and take care of some issues or they will be seeking elsewhere for a place to live.<BR>
<BR>
Bejor Thex &#8211; Proud Leader of the Royal Family of Thex<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
